fr:mainmatter.fr:p:
For the \rightarrow  E \Rightarrow  rule

\frac {\begin {array}{cc}            \Gamma  \vdash  e_1 : A \rightarrow  B             & \Gamma  \vdash  e_2 : A            \end {array}}         {\Gamma  \vdash  e_1 e_2 : B}

while there are 2^3=8 variations, only four are mode-correct:

\frac {\begin {array}{cc}            \Gamma  \vdash  e_1 \Rightarrow  A \rightarrow  B             & \Gamma  \vdash  e_2 \Rightarrow  A            \end {array}}         {\Gamma  \vdash  e_1 e_2 \Rightarrow  B}

\frac {\begin {array}{cc}            \Gamma  \vdash  e_1 \Rightarrow  A \rightarrow  B             & \Gamma  \vdash  e_2 \Leftarrow  A            \end {array}}         {\Gamma  \vdash  e_1 e_2 \Rightarrow  B}

\frac {\begin {array}{cc}            \Gamma  \vdash  e_1 \Rightarrow  A \rightarrow  B             & \Gamma  \vdash  e_2 \Leftarrow  A            \end {array}}         {\Gamma  \vdash  e_1 e_2 \Leftarrow  B}

\frac {\begin {array}{cc}            \Gamma  \vdash  e_1 \Leftarrow  A \rightarrow  B             & \Gamma  \vdash  e_2 \Rightarrow  A            \end {array}}         {\Gamma  \vdash  e_1 e_2 \Leftarrow  B}

The last rule seems questionable, because A is unknown in the conclusion, yet the
first premise checks e_1 against A\rightarrow  B. However, the rule is mode-correct,
because the second premise synthesizes the type A, which is then used to check e_1
against A \rightarrow  B. The order of premises is, therefore, important, not for
determining the meaning of the rule, but where the strategy of applying the rule is
concerned. A strategy is effectively a set of permutations of the premises; in this case,
there are two possible strategies, one of which is effective.

An example of a rule that is not mode-correct is the following:
\frac {\begin {array}{cc} \Gamma \vdash e_1 \Leftarrow A \rightarrow B & \Gamma \vdash e_2 \Leftarrow A \end {array}} {\Gamma \vdash e_1 e_2 \Leftarrow B}
While the type B is known from the conclusion, the type A \rightarrow B is unknown when deriving the first premise, because the type A is unknown and cannot be derived. For the same reason, the second premise \Gamma \vdash e_2 \Leftarrow A is not mode-correct.
